body:
(Title is not entirely accurate, please see below)
The following code in C# will generate a png image that has 36666 in width, but only the first 32767 pixels in width will be correctly generated.
```
                const int TEST_WIDTH = 36666;
                SKPath testPath = new SKPath();
                // A straight horizontal path covering the full width
                testPath.MoveTo(new SKPoint(0, 100));
                testPath.LineTo(TEST_WIDTH, 100);
                // Configure paint
                SKPaint testPaint = new SKPaint
                {
                    Style = SKPaintStyle.Stroke,
                    Color = SKColors.Red,
                    StrokeWidth = 50,
                    StrokeCap = SKStrokeCap.Cyan
                };
                // Save to file
                var bitMap = new SKBitmap(TEST_WIDTH, 200);
                SKCanvas imageCanvas = new SKCanvas(bitMap);
                imageCanvas.DrawPath(testPath, testPaint);
                using (Stream stream = File.OpenWrite('path to png file'))
                {
                    SKData data = SKImage.FromBitmap(bitMap).Encode(SKEncodedImageFormat.Png, 100);
                    data.SaveTo(stream);
                }
```
The resulting image, if opened with Gimp or similar tools, will have a horizontal stroke that only spans to the 32767th pixel in x.

This is found in a Xamarin.Forms project, tested on Nexus 6P running Android 8.1 and iPhone 6s running iOS 11.2.6.
